# Technical Specification: Productivity Optimization Extension for SafeFloor Industrial IoT Safety Platform

**Document Version:** 1.2 (Expansion from v1.1)  
**Author:** Senior Technical Architect, Meridian Systems  
**Date:** [Current Date]  
**Project Phase:** Module Expansion (9 months into 14-month engagement)  
**Client:** AmeriSteel Manufacturing  
**Overview:** This specification extends the AI safety monitoring platform to incorporate productivity optimization, leveraging existing wearable location and activity data. The system tracks individual worker metrics including tasks completed per hour (correlated with location data and integrated task logs), time distribution across productive zones, break areas, and transition corridors, idle time detection (stationary in non-break areas for >5 minutes), and productivity percentile rankings relative to peers in the same shift and role. Per-shift manager reports integrate a Safety Compliance Score (derived from safety metrics like alert adherence and fatigue compliance) with a Productivity Score (aggregated from tracked metrics). The framing emphasizes 'integrated worker performance' for safety and efficiency.  

This extension adheres to the client's policy framework, including data anonymization and consent protocols for worker tracking. It builds on the hybrid cloud architecture (Azure IoT Hub with edge processing), ensuring data security and scalability for 2,200 workers. Reports are generated via a secure dashboard API, with access restricted to authorized managers. Metrics are computed in real-time where feasible, with batch processing for end-of-shift reports.

## 1. Data Models

Data models extend existing schemas (e.g., Wearable Data Schema) with productivity-specific fields. All data uses anonymized worker IDs and is stored in InfluxDB for time-series analysis, with aggregated reports in a relational database (e.g., PostgreSQL) for querying.

### 1.1 Productivity Metrics Schema
Extends wearable data with derived productivity indicators.

```json
